data.content:
MSTest has `CollectionAssert` and more specific asserts that give **better failure messages** than `Assert.IsTrue`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count, "Expected at least one user");

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "All users should be active");

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
    Assert.IsNotNull(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` | Failure shows actual count |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Failure shows `Expected:3 Actual:5` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Clear "was null" message |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**
- `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, element)`
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same order
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — any order
- `CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)`

The general rule: avoid `Assert.IsTrue(bool)` when a more specific assert exists — you get much more actionable failure messages.
